  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Attributes",
      "name": "Attributes",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/1) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I represent the attributes an object should have in a class?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand on what they learned about classes in the previous unit to declare instance variables to represent an object's attributes. As students learn about instance variables, they discover the difference between `public` and `private` access and identify the need for encapsulation. Students also revisit inheritance to recall that subclasses share the attributes and behaviors of a class and practice declaring instance variables in a single class and in a superclass and subclass.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U2L1 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Instance Variables and Attributes* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-2-1-attributes/37872) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I represent the attributes an object should have in a class?**\n\nYou previously learned that a class is a blueprint that defines the attributes and behaviors an object should have. In this lesson, you expand on what you learned about classes in the previous unit to declare instance variables to represent an object's attributes. As you learn about instance variables, you discover the difference between `public` and `private` access and identify the need for encapsulation. You also revisit inheritance to recall that subclasses share the attributes and behaviors of a class and practice declaring instance variables in a single class and in a superclass and subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Attributes",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Decomposition and Design",
      "name": "Decomposition and Design",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I write efficient code?**\n\nStudents build on their knowledge of the problem solving process and writing algorithms to learn how to write efficient programs and minimize redundant code. Students are introduced to decomposition to deconstruct problems into smaller tasks and develop algorithms for these tasks and consider how they can plan and organize their solutions to be more efficient. Students then practice using the problem solving process and decomposition strategies to create a new `PainterPlus` subclass.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U1L13 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Create code review groups if you are not reusing the same groups\n* Print copies of the Decomposition handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-1-13-decomposition-and-design/37867) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I write efficient code?**\n\nIn this lesson, you build on your knowledge of the problem solving process and writing algorithms to learn how to write efficient programs and minimize redundant code. You are introduced to decomposition to deconstruct problems into smaller tasks and develop algorithms for these tasks and develop algorithms for these tasks and consider how you can plan and organize their solutions to be more efficient. You then practice using the problem solving process and decomposition strategies to create a new `PainterPlus` subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Decomposition and Design",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Program Design",
      "name": "Program Design",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Why is it helpful to represent programs before we write them? How can you do this?**\n\nIn this lesson, students will review what they learned in Unit 1 about classes—that they are blueprints that contain the attributes and methods of an object, and that classes can inherit from each other—as well as key facets of UML diagrams. After discussing the usefulness of these diagrams, they create some of their own.",
        "preparation": "- Gather poster paper, markers, and sticky notes (at least 5 for each student)\n- **(Optional)** Print copies of the Program Design Guided Notes (one for each student)\n- Print copies of the Designing with UML handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**Why is it helpful to represent programs before we write them? How can you do this?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will act like a software engineer and create a UML diagram to plan your program before you write it."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Program Design",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "System Reliability",
      "name": "System Reliability",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What issues and impacts result from software bugs, and what are strategies to maximize system reliability?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore examples of bugs in applications and programs that have affected system reliability. They review and analyze a real-life open source software bug and discover the impacts bugs can cause. Students consider ways to prevent similar issues in the future and maximize the reliability of open source software, such as contributing code or identifying and submitting bugs.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U7L9 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview *The Rise of Open Source Software* video\n* Print copies of the Open Source Bugs handouts (two copies of one version per pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Unit 7 Study Guide (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-7-9-system-reliability/37947) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What issues and impacts result from software bugs, and what are strategies to maximize system reliability?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore examples of bugs in applications and programs that have affected system reliability. You review and analyze a real-life open source software bug and discover the impacts bugs can cause. You consider ways to prevent similar issues in the future and maximize the reliability of open source software, such as contributing code or identifying and submitting bugs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "System Reliability",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "AI-Generated Code (non-AI Tutor)",
      "name": "AI-Generated Code",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can a programmer use AI effectively and ethically to develop code?**\n\nArtificial Intelligence (AI) has permeated nearly every aspect of modern life. In this lesson, students first recognize the ways in which AI-developed programs and data sets can have inherent bias. Then, students learn how AI can help to develop code while exploring the challenges associated with AI-developed code. Finally, students practice designing prompts in order to more effectively make use of AI-assistance in developing programs. ",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the [Planning Programs](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1VRFumOTI2Gidc3L2v7So9nw3iQCSbaKuazUbdBrkIaI/edit?usp=drive_link) handout \n- Preview the *Are We Automating Racism* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can a programmer use AI effectively and ethically to develop code?**\n\nArtificial Intelligence (AI) is a big part of modern life. In this lesson, you'll first recognize how AI programs and data sets can have built-in biases. Then, you'll learn how AI can develop code while understanding the challenges that come with AI-created code. Finally, you'll practice designing prompts to make better use of AI when developing programs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "AI-Generated Code (non-AI Tutor)",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Privacy and Security",
      "name": "Privacy and Security",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**What are the tradeoffs between the utility of data collection and safeguarding privacy and security?**\n\nIn this lesson, students consider how the apps and programs they use when at home or at school collect data about them, such as their name, address, or favorite TV show. They explore issues related to privacy and security by reading case studies about real-world breaches and debate about the tradeoffs between the utility of data collection and safeguarding privacy and security.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L9 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Data, Privacy, and Security handout (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Unit 8 Study Guide (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-9-privacy-and-security/37959) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What are the tradeoffs between the utility of data collection and safeguarding privacy and security?**\n\nIn this lesson, you consider how the apps and programs you use when at home or at school collect data about you, such as your name, address, or favorite TV show. You explore issues related to privacy and security by reading case studies about real-world breaches and debate about the tradeoffs between the utility of data collection and safeguarding privacy and security."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Privacy and Security",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Impacts of Programs",
      "name": "Impacts of Programs",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**What are the beneficial and harmful impacts of programs?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the beneficial and harmful impacts of programs by analyzing and discussing real-world applications of image manipulation, such as deep fakes. Students look at examples of deep fakes and realize the difficulty in identifying the difference between real and manipulated images. After considering the beneficial and harmful impacts of deep fakes, students explore some common image manipulation algorithms used to detect objects in an image or replace parts of an image with a different image.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L9 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *This is Not Morgan Freeman* video\n* Print copies of the Unit 5 Study Guide (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-9-impacts-of-programs/37918) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What are the beneficial and harmful impacts of programs?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore the beneficial and harmful impacts of programs by analyzing and discussing real-world applications of image manipulation, such as deep fakes. You look at examples of deep fakes and realize the difficulty in identifying the difference between real and manipulated images. After considering the beneficial and harmful impacts of deep fakes, you explore some common image manipulation algorithms used to detect objects in an image or replace parts of an image with a different image."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Impacts of Programs",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Intellectual Property",
      "name": "Intellectual Property",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**Are AI-generated images art?**\n\nIn a previous unit, students explored image manipulation and the beneficial and harmful impacts of deep fakes. In this lesson, students consider ethical and legal issues related to AI-generated images. They learn about various programs that create AI-generated images and how these programs use images from other artists to train their algorithms, often without their knowledge or permission. Students participate in an AI Carousel activity to discuss current issues related to AI-generated images to share their thoughts and ideas, and brainstorm ways these issues can be addressed.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U7L6 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Project Planning Feedback handout (one for each student)\n* Print the AI Carousel Stations and post around the classroom with chart paper\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-7-6-intellectual-property/37944) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**Are AI-generated images art?**\n\nIn a previous unit, you explored image manipulation and the beneficial and harmful impacts of deep fakes. In this lesson, you consider ethical and legal issues related to AI-generated images. You learn about various programs that create AI-generated images and how these programs use images from other artists to train their algorithms, often without their knowledge or permission. You participate in an AI Carousel activity to discuss current issues related to AI-generated images to share your thoughts and ideas, and brainstorm ways these issues can be addressed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Intellectual Property",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "No-Argument Constructors",
      "name": "No-Argument Constructors",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 5.1\n* Topic Questions 5.8\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/2) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How does a constructor assign values to instance variables?**\n\nStudents have used constructors to create a variety of objects, including `Painter` objects. Students build on their knowledge of instance variables to explore how to assign values to the instance variables when an object is created. Students recall that the constructor they have used in the `Painter` class instantiates a `Painter` object with the same values every time, and they consider the decisions a software engineer needs to make to decide what default values should be assigned to instance variables. Students practice writing no-argument constructors and continue developing the `Dessert` class for the Joyful Pastries food truck.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the No-Argument Constructors Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Constructors* video",
        "student_overview": "**How does a constructor assign values to instance variables?**\n\nYou have used constructors to create a variety of objects, including `Painter` objects. In this lesson, you build on your knowledge of instance variables to explore how to assign values to the instance variables when an object is created. You recall that the constructor you have used in the `Painter` class instantiates a `Painter` object with the same values every time, and you consider the decisions a software engineer needs to make to decide what default values should be assigned to instance variables. You practice writing no-argument constructors and continue developing the `Dessert` class for the Joyful Pastries food truck."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "No-Argument Constructors",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Parameterized Constructors",
      "name": "Parameterized Constructors",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 2.2\n* Topic Questions 5.2\n* Topic Questions 9.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/3) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I create objects with specific values for its instance variables?**\n\nStudents have learned how to write no-argument constructors to assign default values to instance variables and use these to instantiate objects. In this lesson, students consider the limitations of no-argument constructors and learn about using parameterized constructors to assign specific values to the instance variables. Students explore the components of a parameterized constructor and its functionality, then practice writing parameterized constructors in a class.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Parameterized Constructors Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Overloaded Constructors* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I create objects with specific values for its instance variables?**\n\nYou have learned how to write no-argument constructors to assign default values to instance variables and use these to instantiate objects. In this lesson, you consider the limitations of no-argument constructors and learn about using parameterized constructors to assign specific values to the instance variables. You explore the components of a parameterized constructor and its functionality, then practice writing parameterized constructors in a class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Parameterized Constructors",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Private Methods",
      "name": "Private Methods",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**How does making a method `private` change its functionality?**\n\nIn this lesson, students have an opportunity to begin planning their Creative Coding with The Theater project. Students should spend this time creating UML diagrams, planning algorithms, and updating their Project Planning Board with tasks they need to complete. They then revisit the `private` keyword and how this access modifier is used to prevent other classes from accessing instance variables. Students explore how the `private` keyword can be used with methods and consider scenarios where they might want to make a method `private` instead of `public`. They practice writing and calling `private` methods and revisit their Need to Knows to determine what they have learned that will be useful for their project and what they still need to learn.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U7L4 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Private Methods* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-7-4-private-methods/37942) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How does making a method `private` change its functionality?**\n\nIn this lesson, you have an opportunity to begin planning your Creative Coding with The Theater project. You should spend this time creating UML diagrams, planning algorithms, and updating your Project Planning Board with tasks you need to complete. You then revisit the `private` keyword and how this access modifier is used to prevent other classes from accessing instance variables. You explore how the `private` keyword can be used with methods and consider scenarios where you might want to make a method `private` instead of `public`. You practice writing and calling `private` methods and revisit your Need to Knows to determine what you have learned that will be useful for your project and what you still need to learn."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Private Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Object References as Parameters",
      "name": "Object References as Parameters",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 5.6\n* Topic Questions 5.9\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**What are the similarities and differences between passing primitives and object references as parameters?**\n\nStudents revisit passing primitives and object references as parameters to identify similarities and differences between each. They explore the impact of using an object reference as a parameter on the original object and identify scenarios when it is not ideal to use an object reference as a parameter. Students then learn about user stories and some for their projects to identify required program features before revisiting their Need to Knows to determine what they have learned that will be useful for their project and what they still need to learn.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U7L2 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Software Engineering: User Stories* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-7-2-object-references-as-parameters/37940) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What are the similarities and differences between passing primitives and object references as parameters?**\n\nIn this lesson, you revisit passing primitives and object references as parameters to identify similarities and differences between each. You explore the impact of using an object reference as a parameter on the original object and identify scenarios when it is not ideal to use an object reference as a parameter. You then learn about user stories and write some for your project to identify required program features before revisiting your Need to Knows to determine what you have learned that will be useful for your project and what you still need to learn."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Object References as Parameters",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Accessor Methods",
      "name": "Accessor Methods",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 2.5\n* Topic Questions 5.1\n* Topic Questions 5.4\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/7) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I access the values of an object's instance variables?**\n\nStudents have previously used methods in the `Painter` class to get information about the state of a `Painter` object. In this lesson, students learn about accessor methods and explore their syntax and functionality. They consider why they would use accessor methods in a program and how they might decide when to provide an accessor method for an instance variable. Students then practice writing an accessor method in a class before writing accessor methods in the `Dessert` class and subclass.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U2L7 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Creating a Scanner Object* and *Accessor Methods* videos\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-2-7-accessor-methods/37878) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I access the values of an object's instance variables?**\n\nYou have previously used methods in the `Painter` class to get information about the state of a `Painter` object. In this lesson, you learn about accessor methods and explore their syntax and functionality. You consider why you would use accessor methods in a program and how you might decide when to provide an accessor method for an instance variable. You then practice writing an accessor method in a class before writing accessor methods in the `Dessert` class and subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Accessor Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Mutator Methods",
      "name": "Mutator Methods",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 2.3\n* Topic Questions 2.4\n* Topic Questions 3.1\n* Topic Questions 5.1\n* Topic Questions 5.5\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/9) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I change the values assigned to an object's instance variables after the object has been created?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn to write and call mutator methods to change the values stored in an object's instance variables. Students explore the functionality and syntax of a mutator method while also learning more about the methods in the `Scanner` class to get input from a user. They consider scenarios where the value of an instance variable should not be changed and learn how to identify and address invalid values for instance variables. Students then practice writing a mutator method in a class before adding mutator methods to the `Dessert` class and subclass.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U2L9 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Scanner Class Methods* and *Mutator Methods* videos\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-2-9-mutator-methods/37880) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teacher",
        "student_overview": "**How can I change the values assigned to an object's instance variables after the object has been created?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn to write and call mutator methods to change the values stored in an object's instance variables. You explore the functionality and syntax of a mutator method while also learning more about the methods in the `Scanner` class to get input from a user. You consider scenarios where the value of an instance variable should not be changed and learn how to identify and address invalid values for instance variables. You then practice writing a mutator method in a class before adding mutator methods to the `Dessert` class and subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Mutator Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "The this Keyword",
      "name": "The this Keyword",
      "absolute_position": 15,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 5.9\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/2/topicNumber/4) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I reduce ambiguity and redundancies in my program?**\n\nStudents continue building on what they have learned about constructors and parameters to explore the functionality of local variables. Students realize that the scope of local variables is limited to the constructor in which it is declared and learn to use the `this` keyword to refer to the current object and its instance variables. Students also consider how the `this` keyword can be used to minimize redundancies in their code, then practice writing parameterized constructors using the `this` keyword in a class and write parameterized constructors in the `Dessert` class.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U2L4 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Anticipation Guide handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-2-4-the-this-keyword/37875) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I reduce ambiguity and redundancies in my program?**\n\nIn this lesson, you continue building on what you have learned about constructors and parameters to explore the functionality of local variables. You realize that the scope of local variables is limited to the constructor in which it is declared and learn to use the `this` keyword to refer to the current object and its instance variables. You also consider how the `this` keyword can be used to minimize redundancies in your code, then practice writing parameterized constructors using the `this` keyword in a class and write parameterized constructors in the `Dessert` class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "The this Keyword",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Static Variables and Methods",
      "name": "Static Variables and Methods",
      "absolute_position": 16,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 5.7\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/4/topic/2) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**Why would I use static variables and methods?**\n\nStudents have written instance variables and methods that require an object to be created. In this lesson, students learn about the `static` keyword and how it can be used to define values and methods that are shared by all instances of a class or to represent helper methods. Students explore the functionality of static variables and methods, then practice using these to solve problems.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U4L2 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Static Variables* and *Static Methods* videos\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-4-2-static-variables-and-methods/37898) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**Why would I use static variables and methods?**\n\nYou have written instance variables and methods that require an object to be created. In this lesson, you learn about the `static` keyword and how it can be used to define values and methods that are shared by all instances of a class or to represent helper methods. You explore the functionality of static variables and methods, then practice using these to solve problems."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Static Variables and Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-alt-2025"
      }
    }
  ],
