  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "80b56272-cb90-4f09-a299-fd2cab1f9687",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous unit, you learned about the characteristics of software engineers and began to develop your software engineering skills. We will be learning more about the structure and design of classes in Java programs and continue to use software engineering characteristics and skills to make design decisions.",
        "name": "Software Engineering Goals",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "80b56272-cb90-4f09-a299-fd2cab1f9687",
        "lesson_activity.key": "144f63e3-6716-4b2a-94f3-28149173c2f8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4be82e0-2eaa-4d47-a487-9b8a604bdae4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What software engineering characteristics do you want to work on in this unit? How will you know you grew in this area by the end of the unit?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share characteristics and skills that they want to improve and identify goals.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nStudents can choose any characteristic or skill they want to improve regardless of whether or not it is an area for improvement. Students can choose a characteristic that is a strength that they want to further develop as an anchor for upcoming units, or they can choose a characteristic that is an area for improvement."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4be82e0-2eaa-4d47-a487-9b8a604bdae4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "144f63e3-6716-4b2a-94f3-28149173c2f8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a57326e3-79d7-49e4-bb2a-c404bf8efe42",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a57326e3-79d7-49e4-bb2a-c404bf8efe42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5666b792-e1c1-404f-817e-342aa89727d4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous unit, we learned that classes define the attributes and behaviors of an object. We created subclasses of the `Painter` class and wrote methods in these subclasses to give our `Painter` objects new behaviors. Today, we're going to take a look at how we define attributes in a class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5666b792-e1c1-404f-817e-342aa89727d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "def31377-4f3d-444f-a133-db3bb05cd86e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Attributes"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "def31377-4f3d-444f-a133-db3bb05cd86e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "372280ce-b3a3-4aab-a65c-2b16e614ad01",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the classes in the program have `private` variables and that the tester class attempts to access and print the values for these variables. Students also notice the error that is caused by trying to access and print these values and may wonder why these variables are `private`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The error on this program is intentional so students can see that they cannot directly refer to the instance variables of an object. Prompt students to consider possible causes for this error and ways they might correct it."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "372280ce-b3a3-4aab-a65c-2b16e614ad01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "16c78b97-e716-46e5-b7a5-de2be0e8ad0a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall the definition of *class* and *object*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Declaring Instance Variables",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Classes and Attributes"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "16c78b97-e716-46e5-b7a5-de2be0e8ad0a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1fba2424-e39f-46c4-9fa3-7ca3d0841a2c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to share the difference between `private` and `public` and what happened in the program when they changed the instance variables. Ask additional guiding questions, such as:\n* *Why do you think the instance variables are `private`?*\n* *Some of the instance variables are repeated in multiple classes. How do you think we could eliminate the redundancies in these classes?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1fba2424-e39f-46c4-9fa3-7ca3d0841a2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0db02ab-43b8-4985-93e1-7cbeab4068d6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Instance Variables and Attributes*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0db02ab-43b8-4985-93e1-7cbeab4068d6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ec02c9c-ca28-4a00-9d2e-5119b7240220",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***instance variable***.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax for declaring an instance variable:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The instance variable is `private`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The data type for the instance variable and introduce the `double` data type\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The name of the instance variable\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why do you think these are called instance variables instead of just variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that when they create an object, they are creating an instance of a class. An object then gets its own copy of the attributes and methods defined in the class. They realize that these are called instance variables because they define the attributes an object should have, so each object gets its own copy of these variables.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ec02c9c-ca28-4a00-9d2e-5119b7240220",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5039b041-f987-43f3-adbc-37d7abbf0690",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that an object gets a copy of the instance variables that are defined in the class when it is instantiated.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to practice writing instance variables in a class.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Declaring Instance Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5039b041-f987-43f3-adbc-37d7abbf0690",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57955b40-23c4-4ed3-a903-e4141039fba3",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall the definition of *inheritance* and how a subclass shares the attributes and behaviors of the superclass.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 6 to complete Levels 6 and 7 on Code Studio. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Inheritance Hierarchies",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Refactoring Code"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57955b40-23c4-4ed3-a903-e4141039fba3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c171920d-8587-4420-8d63-80a467dcf929",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***access modifier*** and ***encapsulation***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When would encapsulation be useful?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share that encapsulation protects the attributes of a class and ensures that only the class can control what is stored. They might also suggest that this prevents accidental or direct access to the attributes, especially in programs where some attributes should not be accessed or modified without some form of verification.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to consider attributes that they might not want to be changed by other parts of a program, such as a social security number or student ID. Ask students to consider the implications of these values being `public` and how making instance variables `private` can prevent potential issues."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c171920d-8587-4420-8d63-80a467dcf929",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49a3abbf-ab8c-46ce-81d7-41b02629eaf7",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***DRY principle***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider how they could apply the DRY principle to the example classes.\n\nYou could also prompt students to consider what additional code they would have to write in the `PainterPlus` class if it was not a subclass of the `Painter` class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49a3abbf-ab8c-46ce-81d7-41b02629eaf7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6299fe4-f71e-42c4-9e30-2a58d20baf75",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***refactor***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 8 to complete Levels 8 and 9. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 8, then continue to Level 9 to create the `Dessert` class and a `Dessert` subclass.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The Food Truck",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and declaring instance variables in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6299fe4-f71e-42c4-9e30-2a58d20baf75",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9d67196-762f-4968-9823-f6387ba82486",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` classes to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9d67196-762f-4968-9823-f6387ba82486",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c223b81d-e937-418f-9cad-577ffb5a663d",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` classes to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c223b81d-e937-418f-9cad-577ffb5a663d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "18542fed-d558-4458-bf80-c73e84af0439"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13bd1eb5-beb1-471b-a33b-6a86d5becd52",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to write classes with instance variables to represent an object's attributes and methods to represent its behaviors! With this knowledge, we can create classes to represent just about any type of object we need for our programs.",
        "name": "Three W's",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13bd1eb5-beb1-471b-a33b-6a86d5becd52",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56427550-c24e-4c01-a82f-be0e6053d334"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fd2a39f2-1797-44e2-81d9-0f7b4978f840",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight the concepts and vocabulary they learned in this lesson, such as instance variables and encapsulation. Students also recall the difference between `public` and `private` access and might also make connections with the attributes in the `Painter` class. They should realize that they now have the knowledge to start designing their own classes from scratch instead of depending only on existing classes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 2 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fd2a39f2-1797-44e2-81d9-0f7b4978f840",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56427550-c24e-4c01-a82f-be0e6053d334"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00952c74-93f4-46e0-aca2-6bfdd859a27d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00952c74-93f4-46e0-aca2-6bfdd859a27d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56427550-c24e-4c01-a82f-be0e6053d334"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cabd1a20-861f-4b25-82fd-27c9afe0e910",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cabd1a20-861f-4b25-82fd-27c9afe0e910",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56427550-c24e-4c01-a82f-be0e6053d334"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "449762a9-06ac-4dfd-b3d4-35cb2693d9ab",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "449762a9-06ac-4dfd-b3d4-35cb2693d9ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56427550-c24e-4c01-a82f-be0e6053d334"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4997f76b-c9e2-450f-bd7d-7c27582e458b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Computer science is all about problem-solving. Solving problems is a core component of a software engineer's work, and we have learned about ways to create and improve solutions in The Neighborhood. Let's consider how we solve problems in our daily lives.",
        "name": "Solving Problems",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4997f76b-c9e2-450f-bd7d-7c27582e458b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5fd87d3-f5ca-42d4-8ea8-dde2b328063c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3fa51c7a-0ae1-4f22-8dc8-ad9c485e4e07",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work with their groups to write an algorithm for the scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What process did you take to decide on your algorithm?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share the approaches they took to develop their algorithm. Students discuss how they broke the problem down into smaller tasks, such as sorting the colors into piles and then counting the number of M&M's in each pile.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to identify the steps they took to solve the problem and consider how these steps are related to smaller chunks of the larger problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3fa51c7a-0ae1-4f22-8dc8-ad9c485e4e07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5fd87d3-f5ca-42d4-8ea8-dde2b328063c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "617b6635-140e-402f-a068-2e5f0c642b1c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Decomposition"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "617b6635-140e-402f-a068-2e5f0c642b1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7cf34911-92cc-4594-8d72-5d32f63207a3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes, problems are so big that we need to break them down into manageable tasks first. This process is called decomposition, and we will learn how to use this approach to break down problems.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7cf34911-92cc-4594-8d72-5d32f63207a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9010f63-f125-4b79-9ad2-e9008c89d601",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***decomposition***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Revisit the scenario from the warm up or an example of a personal interest or daily activity. Briefly discuss how the scenario would be broken down into specific tasks or steps."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9010f63-f125-4b79-9ad2-e9008c89d601",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd8272d5-3d99-4730-907f-fbed87074296",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to complete Levels 1 through 4. Students investigate the program by making modifications to the program as prompted and observing the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Decomposition"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd8272d5-3d99-4730-907f-fbed87074296",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e428521f-e3f7-4929-9da8-5a4eb85ed7fc",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to share what the `setPaint()` method does and how they might use this method in their programs. You could also ask students to identify how the `setPaint()` method is similar and different from the `getMyPaint()` method.\n\nYou do not need to discuss accessor or mutator methods here, as these topics are discussed in an upcoming lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e428521f-e3f7-4929-9da8-5a4eb85ed7fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "057cb6ff-461f-43cd-993f-a2915c18df64",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When software engineers develop solutions, they try to account for potential errors and different ways a user might use the program. However, they have to be careful about being redundant to keep their programs efficient.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Developing Efficient Solutions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "057cb6ff-461f-43cd-993f-a2915c18df64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "280ceb08-03cc-4994-867d-d33f560b9f30",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does it mean to you for something to be efficient?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest definitions and examples, such as being fast or organized. Students might share examples from their personal lives, such as something being energy-efficient or having tools and resources to make chores or work more efficient.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nPrompt students to consider examples where the lack of organization or resources cause a task to be inefficient. For example, you could ask students to compare washing dishes by hand and using a dishwasher. Have students share reasons why one approach to completing the task is more efficient than the other, such as the amount of time and energy it takes to complete the task."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "280ceb08-03cc-4994-867d-d33f560b9f30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b112c237-0412-42dd-93f7-168bc3510b82",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***redundant code*** and ***efficient***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to make connections between efficiency in daily tasks and efficiency in writing code. Have students consider why efficiency in programs would be important and guide them to realize how this helps with development, maintainability, and the overall speed of the program."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b112c237-0412-42dd-93f7-168bc3510b82",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3c13526-3b45-4bfb-a384-1860ab791af6",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can we make sure we are writing efficient code?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest eliminating redundant code by writing methods for repetitive tasks. They may also suggest writing methods that perform only one task and calling these from other methods that represent larger tasks.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nPrompt students to consider the code they saw in the Investigate level and what structures were implemented to make writing and editing the code more efficient."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3c13526-3b45-4bfb-a384-1860ab791af6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39b727bf-2220-497a-8d16-8def91209b9d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have used the problem solving process to break down problems and plan your algorithms. When we do this, it can help us identify any repetitive tasks that we can write methods for. These methods then represent a smaller task as part of the larger solution and consist of their own algorithms. To plan algorithms for a problem or a method, you have actually been using a tool that software engineers often use to plan their own algorithms.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39b727bf-2220-497a-8d16-8def91209b9d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46ed27e3-3b71-4429-b52b-5e8f9371aaf0",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***pseudocode***."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46ed27e3-3b71-4429-b52b-5e8f9371aaf0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68a86f6b-8b71-4fd8-bb94-57d76902cff0",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As you work through these problems, use the problem solving process and decomposition strategies to break them down into manageable tasks. Write your algorithms in pseudocode so you can easily implement and refine them in Java.",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Creating Murals",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68a86f6b-8b71-4fd8-bb94-57d76902cff0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "328c1e01-4a35-482a-b41d-eaaea8541541",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Decomposition handout.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to choose one of the problems and use the problem solving process to plan their solution and write pseudocode for their algorithms.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize the use of natural language when writing pseudocode. Allow students to write their pseudocode in whichever language they are most comfortable to support the focus on planning their algorithms rather than focusing on specific structures or languages."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "328c1e01-4a35-482a-b41d-eaaea8541541",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89c47455-0881-4467-a115-b8575ac71f04",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 6, then continue to Level 6 to create a subclass of the `PainterPlus` class and implement their algorithm for their chosen problem.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Decomposing a Problem",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of planning and using decomposition, the problem solving process, and pseudocode to plan and implement algorithms."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89c47455-0881-4467-a115-b8575ac71f04",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ce5fc1d-6fe9-4692-8477-c63fde3e1ded",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our new `PainterPlus` subclass to the Backpack. Anytime we make changes to our programs, it is helpful to commit our work in case we need to go back to a previous version.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ce5fc1d-6fe9-4692-8477-c63fde3e1ded",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5dfa6b5a-8f88-4d7d-a776-aeae560b7550",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their new `PainterPlus` subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5dfa6b5a-8f88-4d7d-a776-aeae560b7550",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fbb62d47-d6c6-4b4e-b021-93bef3973423",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we write new code, getting feedback from our peers is helpful to make sure we have met the requirements of the problem efficiently.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "Code Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fbb62d47-d6c6-4b4e-b021-93bef3973423",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5dfaf47e-131c-4575-95c2-538edcd43879",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to have students participate in the Code Review Call and Response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to conduct a code review on their chosen problem.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be at different points when it is time for the code review. Emphasize to students that their work does not need to be completed to get feedback. Remind students that the problem-solving and development process is iterative and that receiving feedback from peers while they are working can help give them additional insights, perspectives, and guidance.\n\nConducting code reviews on choice levels is slightly different than on single levels. To conduct a code review on a choice level:\n1. Students select the level they completed to request a code review on their work.\n2. Students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page.\n3. Students select the level their peers completed to give feedback on their work.\n\nTo review the feedback given on their work, students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page, then select the level they completed. Students should then review the feedback and make improvements to their code and repeat the process as needed until they are satisfied with their solution."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5dfaf47e-131c-4575-95c2-538edcd43879",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1753650e-0beb-4e5d-a95f-779c3b3b190e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "270b70fd-ba6f-494b-a412-2b0664574cc9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have made a lot of progress developing your software engineering skills. Let's take a moment to reflect on our progress and growth.",
        "name": "Software Engineering Skills",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "270b70fd-ba6f-494b-a412-2b0664574cc9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "11fa587a-7005-4a26-b922-91b5e3eeb204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f3fc4b0-e2e1-4a71-a9ba-cb8fef8c5f87",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How have you grown as a software engineer so far?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share the growth and progress they have made and identify specific characteristics where they feel they have improved.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 1 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f3fc4b0-e2e1-4a71-a9ba-cb8fef8c5f87",
        "lesson_activity.key": "11fa587a-7005-4a26-b922-91b5e3eeb204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa503d84-0716-43f8-aceb-5227e2d90671",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 1 Guide includes an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to reflect on the lesson and the progress they made in developing their software engineering skills and characteristics. Have students respond to the reflection prompt after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and reflect on their personal growth."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa503d84-0716-43f8-aceb-5227e2d90671",
        "lesson_activity.key": "11fa587a-7005-4a26-b922-91b5e3eeb204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "61c3f5e9-f89e-4ccb-8c27-dd01de4462bb",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "61c3f5e9-f89e-4ccb-8c27-dd01de4462bb",
