    {
      "key": "1cc38153-40f4-44cc-a92c-d3c7fc38a26e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1cc38153-40f4-44cc-a92c-d3c7fc38a26e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "11fa587a-7005-4a26-b922-91b5e3eeb204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a475d41c-b695-4e61-88f7-6b658d548fcc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous unit, you learned about the characteristics of software engineers and began to develop your software engineering skills. We will be learning more about the structure and design of classes in Java programs and continue to use software engineering characteristics and skills to make design decisions.",
        "name": "Software Engineering Goals",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a475d41c-b695-4e61-88f7-6b658d548fcc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f2cf62c1-6c53-4d1d-a511-e9988ee977b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9141a014-c7a7-4185-8cce-d44eeffc92d8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Think of a time where you had to prepare to do something, like go on a trip or make a meal. How can having an effective plan make things easier?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students discuss how having a plan can make tasks easier by reducing stress, saving time, and improving organization. They relate these benefits to their own experiences of preparing for activities or projects.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9141a014-c7a7-4185-8cce-d44eeffc92d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f2cf62c1-6c53-4d1d-a511-e9988ee977b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d8092bd5-859c-48ef-983f-a290390df675",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8092bd5-859c-48ef-983f-a290390df675",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b90f628f-955c-4b97-8515-ad128d141c8d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "name": "(Optional) Review",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This section is a 3-question review: what are classes, what are the parts of a UML diagram, and inheritance. If you are confident your students do not need the review, you can skip it, entirely, or just skip the individual questions you . If you are unsure, asking these questions can help you figure out what your students have retained. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b90f628f-955c-4b97-8515-ad128d141c8d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e0dd51eb-3ea8-4dd1-acaa-dc6a17baecc4",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e0dd51eb-3ea8-4dd1-acaa-dc6a17baecc4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ddb2ee3-4d5d-4ec6-b928-a3315a67910d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "One of the tools in a software engineer’s toolbox is to think about how to organize their programs before writing them, and share their ideas with their colleagues. This saves a lot of time later. Today, we’ll practice one way that software engineers organize their thoughts and share ideas before programming. First, let’s ground ourselves in what we already know.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ddb2ee3-4d5d-4ec6-b928-a3315a67910d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de4ee093-fb06-4ca1-9e7a-3b245a4f2129",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is a class?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:**  Students understand that a class in object-oriented programming serves as a blueprint for creating objects, defining their attributes and behaviors. Students may also relate this concept to real-world examples of templates or schematics used to produce specific instances.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the definition of object and class.  \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students label the parts of the UML diagram.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the labels for each part of the UML diagram\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *abstraction* in terms of class design and UML diagrams.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is inheritance?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students mention that inheritance is an object-oriented programming concept where a subclass inherits attributes and behaviors from a superclass.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall that inheritance creates an *is-a* relationship. Demonstrate that arrows are drawn from the subclass to the superclass to represent this relationship."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de4ee093-fb06-4ca1-9e7a-3b245a4f2129",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "403190a5-6752-48f7-9136-90a63821bcd8",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this lesson, you’ll create a UML diagram for an app of your choice. This will help you translate your ideas into a clear, actionable plan for programming. Let's explore how to do this together.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction to UML Diagrams",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "403190a5-6752-48f7-9136-90a63821bcd8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "977391cf-dc93-4ce8-80cb-4a3d3394781f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do these representations have in common? How are they different?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify common elements and differences between the UML diagram and the text description, noting how the diagram provides a structured, visual representation of attributes and methods, while the text offers a descriptive summary of the same information.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do these representations have in common? How are they different?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students compare the UML diagrams and text to see how the diagrams show the relationship between a superclass and its subclasses, while the text describes the attributes and behaviors of each class. They should understand how the diagrams visually represent these relationships and how the text provides the same information in words."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "977391cf-dc93-4ce8-80cb-4a3d3394781f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8bec1300-2487-4eab-85dc-0802a144a61a",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate what a text-description of the Pet-Dog-Cat relationship would look like."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8bec1300-2487-4eab-85dc-0802a144a61a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3031414a-dbcc-48bc-9a5c-7d9e6824ee4a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate what a UML Diagram for the Pet-Dog-Cat relationship would look like.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why might it be helpful to have these representations before you write a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students understand that having UML diagrams and text descriptions helps in planning and organizing the structure of a program, making it easier to write code by providing a clear visual and descriptive reference of the classes and their relationships.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What words in a program description make sense to turn into a class?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify the nouns in a program description as classes and the verbs as behaviors. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students need more guidance, it may be helpful to get them thinking about parts of speech – nouns are often classes, verbs are often methods. If students need it, remind students that a “noun” is a “person, place or thing” and a “verb” is a “thing something or someone can do.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3031414a-dbcc-48bc-9a5c-7d9e6824ee4a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0805ea90-675c-40f6-99db-6cc8b4b90c1a",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Not all nouns should be classes. Which of these is not a class?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify that nouns that do not actively hold or do something do not need to be classes. Students might suggest that these nouns can be attributes of classes. For example, the “length” of the run does not need to hold or do anything and can be an attribute of the run. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0805ea90-675c-40f6-99db-6cc8b4b90c1a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66682416-0ac3-4ff6-a47f-a5476754a9d7",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now it’s time to practice being a software engineer! You'll now have an opportunity to think critically about how you would design a program and communicate that design to others using a UML diagram. ",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Designing with UML",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students have their own program ideas, they can use those as the basis for their UML diagram, as long as the focus remains on turning the idea into a clear diagram. You can remind students that the goal is to practice the process of translating program ideas into a visual plan, rather than developing new ideas from scratch."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66682416-0ac3-4ff6-a47f-a5476754a9d7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "469b8d1b-22cb-43da-8ac9-c014940a43bc",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a poster paper and marker.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to review each project description and select one.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to use their activity guides to plan their UML diagram. Students will circle the nouns in the requirements, underline the verbs, and double the circle around nouns representing classes that should be created.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to use their poster paper to turn their plans into UML diagrams and a program description.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Circulate as students work, offering time reminders, and ask guiding questions to help them identify potential classes and define what each class 'has' and 'does.' Encourage collaboration by asking questions that lead pairs to a shared decision. Celebrate progress, and remind pairs to include both the UML diagram and text description on their poster. Using a visible timer can help students stay aware of how much time remains."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "469b8d1b-22cb-43da-8ac9-c014940a43bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288a3868-4380-4dd6-8cd4-87678017a0e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "019b4a7d-abd9-4977-adff-44dbcf78c212",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It’s exciting to see these ideas coming together! Now that we have a plan, we’ll run it by other people. Since a class diagram is essentially a plan for code, we'll use the same TAG feedback process we apply during code reviews, but with sticky notes. Tell your classmates what in your work you like, ask them questions about why they chose particular classes and offer suggestions.\n",
        "name": "Gallery Walk",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "019b4a7d-abd9-4977-adff-44dbcf78c212",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80d77f7f-efd7-4151-b3bc-81708ab96354"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "744b4ebc-36ba-4a97-8e3e-4b2ad0bbc116",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Distribute: Give each pair several post-it notes, at least five per student.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Direct students to TAG the UML diagrams as they participate in the gallery walk.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Direct students back to their own UML diagrams to review the comments left by their peers. Direct students to write down ideas and thoughts in response to the prompt on a sticky note or scrap piece of paper. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The gallery walk and student reflections can be used as an informal assessment opportunity. Reviewing the comments they leave on various UML diagrams and their responses can give insight into their grasp of class structure and design."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "744b4ebc-36ba-4a97-8e3e-4b2ad0bbc116",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80d77f7f-efd7-4151-b3bc-81708ab96354"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3434c0d7-6a4f-42b6-aa24-ee26df04d4e3",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3434c0d7-6a4f-42b6-aa24-ee26df04d4e3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80d77f7f-efd7-4151-b3bc-81708ab96354"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87c32df2-d264-425e-971e-c49a9d51c2b1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Throughout this year, you've used your software engineer skills to debug your code. Let's think about some examples of bugs in the real world.",
        "name": "Bugs",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87c32df2-d264-425e-971e-c49a9d51c2b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "59e22872-c104-45e3-9423-902d1eb5b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "25a1e78e-7e2b-40da-a77b-63b1804b395c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When have you experienced a bug in an application or program that you use that affected system reliability - a system's ability to function without failure?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of bugs they have experienced, such as a website being down or apps that they use crashing.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "25a1e78e-7e2b-40da-a77b-63b1804b395c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "59e22872-c104-45e3-9423-902d1eb5b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "987ecf93-8c90-4620-afc9-b22d338dde2f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Open Source Bugs"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "987ecf93-8c90-4620-afc9-b22d338dde2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4eb4b7b2-29e2-432b-bd24-b0e686ed1db6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It's impossible to completely prevent all bugs in a program. However, as software engineers, there are actions we can take to quickly identify and resolve bugs before they cause significant issues for users.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4eb4b7b2-29e2-432b-bd24-b0e686ed1db6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0b501eb4-cfe9-49c7-a1cd-b17334e88e29",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***system reliability***.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair two copies of the same version of the Open Source Bugs handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the instructions for the Open Source Bugs activity and have students complete the activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was the bug?*\n* *How widespread was it?*\n* *What is being done to maximize system reliability in the future?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share the bug they reviewed and the impacts resulting from the bug. Students identify the actions that are being taken to prevent these issues in the future and may also suggest additional actions that can be taken to prevent these issues."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0b501eb4-cfe9-49c7-a1cd-b17334e88e29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "322f7b34-b031-4902-9267-da5f150dcde0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *The Rise of Open Source Software*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Maximizing Reliability",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "322f7b34-b031-4902-9267-da5f150dcde0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06803943-d5f6-4e42-b375-0fdadc1f8a18",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers often use existing open source software to develop their own programs. They also may choose to develop new programs and make them open source for other people and software engineers to use in their programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06803943-d5f6-4e42-b375-0fdadc1f8a18",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1606f5b9-68e4-4d90-a858-30db35be62d0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What can you do as software engineers to maximize the reliability of open source software?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest ways to maximize the reliability of open source software, such as contributing code to existing projects or identifying and submitting bugs found in existing projects.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1606f5b9-68e4-4d90-a858-30db35be62d0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffd2019d-9174-4087-9f8c-3bed3d635b3f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a92f2c2-4bec-4aa4-9127-b918a33080b1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "name": "Show What You Know Week",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 7 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a92f2c2-4bec-4aa4-9127-b918a33080b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f4cb60a7-971e-4461-851f-f3a53538c635"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf3ea042-7b9b-4c11-bfb3-362748244f5d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The next five lessons are an opportunity to Show What You Know! We begin with the unit project, then spend a day practicing answering AP-style free-response questions and wrapping up the unit with a multiple-choice assessment. You've learned so much in this unit, and now you're ready to show what you know!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf3ea042-7b9b-4c11-bfb3-362748244f5d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f4cb60a7-971e-4461-851f-f3a53538c635"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6e64211-5b8c-4d07-a9a5-5f1ccf41a0eb",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Unit 7 Study Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Show What You Know Week.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the goals of the project workdays.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students update their Project Planning Board and Project Backlog with any tasks they completed, changed, or added.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6e64211-5b8c-4d07-a9a5-5f1ccf41a0eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f4cb60a7-971e-4461-851f-f3a53538c635"
      }
    },
