      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76112b30-cb52-4b52-a677-c1900fd493f8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76112b30-cb52-4b52-a677-c1900fd493f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "83a56575-2a7f-4124-9b63-6bbe66989aa8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "09f03c0a-cf1d-4ed6-81f1-c5824ca4202b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used parameters in our constructors and methods to make our code more flexible and work with different inputs. Let's explore some of the benefits and differences in using primitives and objects as parameters in our programs.",
        "name": "Parameterized Song",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "09f03c0a-cf1d-4ed6-81f1-c5824ca4202b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6b0ca452-5461-48fd-a46e-a3fdfb771536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2432dae-aa0d-441d-a960-81092a30cc7a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the parameterized song problem. Assign pairs to solve the problem with primitives and with objects as parameters.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Try to have an equal number of pairs working with primitives as parameters and objects as parameters."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2432dae-aa0d-441d-a960-81092a30cc7a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6b0ca452-5461-48fd-a46e-a3fdfb771536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f05e1182-de2a-4501-9108-c0f511843f80",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work with their partners to write pseudocode to outline their solution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have pairs with the primitives as parameters compare their solutions with pairs with objects as parameters.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about each solution?*\n* *What do you wonder about each solution?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify similarities and differences between passing primitives and passing object references as parameters. Students may wonder about the impact on original variables and objects when passed as parameters.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may have misconceptions about similarities and differences. Refer back to these throughout the lesson as they are addressed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f05e1182-de2a-4501-9108-c0f511843f80",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6b0ca452-5461-48fd-a46e-a3fdfb771536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f0d7e17-ca60-4aeb-9298-4892ad2efacb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall the difference between primitive and reference variables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Object References as Parameters"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f0d7e17-ca60-4aeb-9298-4892ad2efacb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0a7544c3-e0e6-48e9-a990-a3195cca92c5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the method that uses an object reference as a parameter makes changes to the original object, while the method that uses a primitive value as a parameter does not make changes to the original variable. Students also notice that a method can only access the `private` data of a parameter that is a reference to an object when the parameter is the same type as the method's enclosing class. Students may wonder why the method that uses an object reference makes changes to the original object while the method that uses a primitive value does not make changes to the original value. Students may also wonder if there are scenarios when modifying the original object is not ideal."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0a7544c3-e0e6-48e9-a990-a3195cca92c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a46f5e52-fb72-4dd0-9787-870080b0be83",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall the difference between formal parameters and actual parameters and how these function.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring Parameters",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Object References as Parameters"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a46f5e52-fb72-4dd0-9787-870080b0be83",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c021796e-a3b9-447c-b927-1b97317b0ac6",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask additional guiding questions to help students recall aliases and how this occurs in this program. For example:\n* *The formal parameter gets a copy of the value that is passed. When the actual parameter is an object reference, what is actually copied - the object itself or the object reference?*\n* *When the formal parameter is initialized to a copy of the object reference, what is the relationship between the formal parameter and the original object reference?*\n* *What is it called when two reference variables point to the same object?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c021796e-a3b9-447c-b927-1b97317b0ac6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7812febe-bcfe-4848-8d57-158d923509e9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we have an object reference as a parameter, the value that is passed is a copy of the reference to the object, not the object itself. On the other hand, when we have a primitive as a parameter, a copy of the value is passed. Let's take a closer look at how this works.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Object References as Parameters",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7812febe-bcfe-4848-8d57-158d923509e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "681759e9-55a2-4313-84ed-11ffed4009a2",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate object references and primitives as parameters:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Object references as the actual parameter and the result in the formal parameter\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The formal and actual parameter are aliases\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Primitive values as the actual parameter\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***pass by value***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Accessing `private` data of a parameter in a method\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does the `this` keyword do when it is used as a parameter?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that the `this` keyword refers to the current object. Students identify that using the `this` keyword as a parameter passes the current object in the method call.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "681759e9-55a2-4313-84ed-11ffed4009a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bbb8cc61-dd3e-453a-bb89-e4a5600a61ac",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is this similar to how we have used the `this` keyword before? How is it different?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest similarities and differences, such as using the `this` keyword to refer to the current object and using the `this` keyword to pass the entire object instead of only referring to its instance variables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using the `this` keyword as a method parameter."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bbb8cc61-dd3e-453a-bb89-e4a5600a61ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30afd843-4f24-4786-8fcb-3db18861702f",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Since a copy of the reference is passed when an object reference is used as a parameter, any changes made to the object by the method or constructor impact the original object. There are times when this is ok, but there might be times when we don't want this to happen.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "Practice",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30afd843-4f24-4786-8fcb-3db18861702f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ffe745f9-0f30-4b52-8e8d-de05b314df0b",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When is it ideal to pass objects as parameters? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest passing objects as parameters when a problem requires the original object to be modified by a method or constructor.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ffe745f9-0f30-4b52-8e8d-de05b314df0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39d73249-09f5-4518-8f08-d8c77db1596c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When should we avoid passing objects as parameters? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest avoiding passing objects as parameters when the method or constructor should not modify the original object.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate that when an object reference is a constructor parameter, the instance variable should be initialized with a copy of the referenced object.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to complete choice levels on Levels 6 and 7 to practice using object references as parameters to methods and constructors.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Object References as Parameters",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of using object references as parameters to methods.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of using object references as parameters to methods and constructors."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39d73249-09f5-4518-8f08-d8c77db1596c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa6dcdc3-8628-4511-8f66-1ea47ae4c0c9",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As software engineers, one of our primary goals is to develop software that provides usefulness and value to users. Our goal for the Creative Coding Project is to create a program using The Theater that portrays a personal interest or solves a problem. When we develop programs to convey a personal interest, we typically have an audience in mind that we want to show our work to. When we develop programs to solve a problem, we typically have a specific type of user that we want to benefit from the program.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing User Stories",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa6dcdc3-8628-4511-8f66-1ea47ae4c0c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a325a3b7-14b2-4841-acfa-442187e5be47",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***end user*** and ***user story***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Software Engineering: User Stories*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a325a3b7-14b2-4841-acfa-442187e5be47",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9004f10e-9c4f-453e-a429-fa473561e99b",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate example user stories.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Think about an app or program you use every day. Who are the end users for that app or program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share apps or programs they use and the end users for these. For example, the end users for an app like Instagram might be photographers or influencers, while the end users for a banking app might be the customers of the bank.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What might a user story be for that app or program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest user stories for the app or program they shared. For example, a user story for Instagram might be \"As a user, I want to be able to upload a photo to my profile\", while a user story for a banking app might be \"As a user, I want to be able to check my balance\".",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9004f10e-9c4f-453e-a429-fa473561e99b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0d2fbc4-4068-4cb7-b0e0-01655f8a46d2",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "User stories help inform the features we need to implement in our projects and keep us focused on the experience we want someone using our program to have.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0d2fbc4-4068-4cb7-b0e0-01655f8a46d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc803083-46e7-4f05-b49b-b47b6024272b",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write user stories for their project on page five of their Creative Coding with The Theater Project Planning Guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc803083-46e7-4f05-b49b-b47b6024272b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d97d8d4b-9387-4cce-9d75-7df2db75044b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5046df3b-907d-4935-abee-56f7a8d519ea",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just learned a lot of new information today, which may have even answered some of the Need to Know questions you wrote down about the Creative Coding Project. As we progress through the unit, it is helpful to stop and note what we have learned that is related to or useful for the project.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Need to Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5046df3b-907d-4935-abee-56f7a8d519ea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bbb66ffe-6923-4e77-a43b-8df9cb883d4b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a31254b-4021-4472-825a-7da7ebe559cd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review the questions they wrote in the \"Need to Know\" column on page two of their Creative Coding with The Theater Project Planning Guide. Students add new questions to this column, check off any answered questions, and write the answers to any questions in the \"Learned\" column.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they added to their chart with a partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, you can also have students share as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a31254b-4021-4472-825a-7da7ebe559cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bbb66ffe-6923-4e77-a43b-8df9cb883d4b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ce5ceb4-0021-4864-8a14-94198da54ced",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 7 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
