    {
      "key": "3f36aa04-1231-4715-b509-8d878a4fc80d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Getting input from a user is an important aspect of many apps and programs we use every day. User input makes a program more interactive and adaptable to individual needs and information.",
        "name": "The Scanner Class",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f36aa04-1231-4715-b509-8d878a4fc80d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "38b83156-c5eb-48f6-91fb-e01295c9a43c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2e1d905a-2ae8-4c2d-a725-1c2b9603e9b8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***application programming interface (API)*** and ***library***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Java API.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Creating a Scanner Object*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2e1d905a-2ae8-4c2d-a725-1c2b9603e9b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "38b83156-c5eb-48f6-91fb-e01295c9a43c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "181599f9-bf1b-4f6d-8a70-2f08a65ef906",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `java.util` package and the `Scanner` class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will see the `Scanner` class used in the programs they use today but will not be expected to create `Scanner` objects or call any of its methods. Students will learn more about the methods in the `Scanner` class and practice calling its methods in an upcoming lesson. The goal here is to start exposing students to working with user input alongside familiar program code to build up to writing code to obtain user input on their own."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "181599f9-bf1b-4f6d-8a70-2f08a65ef906",
        "lesson_activity.key": "38b83156-c5eb-48f6-91fb-e01295c9a43c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0fd7f162-5934-4429-be4d-b7d7bdae82ce",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could you use the `Scanner` class in the programs you have written so far?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using the `Scanner` class to prompt the user for starting values to create `Painter` or `Dessert` objects or to enter numbers to perform calculations. Students might also suggest asking users for their name or to enter login information and make connections to apps and programs they use.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nAsk students about specific apps they use on their mobile devices or programs for school work. Have students consider the types of inputs for these apps and programs."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0fd7f162-5934-4429-be4d-b7d7bdae82ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "38b83156-c5eb-48f6-91fb-e01295c9a43c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36435f8d-5c8c-465f-a35f-fd869e74ca21",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36435f8d-5c8c-465f-a35f-fd869e74ca21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5609a98a-2722-4bfd-8ffc-a476c422071d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used encapsulation by declaring instance variables in a class as `private` so that other classes in our programs cannot access them. While this ensures that the data in a class is protected, sometimes we do need a value stored in an instance variable somewhere else in our program. Today, we will learn about accessor methods and how we can use these to provide information about the state of an object to another class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5609a98a-2722-4bfd-8ffc-a476c422071d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "94a12efe-65fc-4656-946d-76cfbfd08404",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Accessor Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "94a12efe-65fc-4656-946d-76cfbfd08404",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ada95a3b-a149-4662-97a4-8fac6c11064d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that there are methods in the class that return the instance variable. They also notice that when these methods are called, they can obtain and print the values stored in the instance variable. Students may wonder why they might use accessor methods and how these methods are similar or different from methods they have written before."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ada95a3b-a149-4662-97a4-8fac6c11064d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "83262302-7954-4529-94eb-398d7209bc05",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to recall method signatures and return type.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Accessor Methods*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "83262302-7954-4529-94eb-398d7209bc05",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74ff927f-8314-4ec3-8f96-2be25926d4e6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results then practice writing an accessor method in a class.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Accessor Methods",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Accessor Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74ff927f-8314-4ec3-8f96-2be25926d4e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb0bd4a1-ddb2-4d5f-920c-9ff81a7de628",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Accessor Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb0bd4a1-ddb2-4d5f-920c-9ff81a7de628",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e11d68a3-7138-41ff-8ec7-06836c27b0a1",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e11d68a3-7138-41ff-8ec7-06836c27b0a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50e310cb-72ec-46cc-94a5-897df9f1df3b",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have written methods that performed a task and did not return any information. We have also used methods in the `Painter` class that did return information, such as the value of its `xLocation` or `yLocation` instance variable. These methods are useful when we want to get information about the state of an object.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Writing Accessor Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50e310cb-72ec-46cc-94a5-897df9f1df3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b7c20f8-b1d2-4e02-8f80-f87a1a588d7e",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***accessor method*** and recall the methods in the `Painter` class.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax for writing an accessor method:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The method is `public` so it can be accessed from outside of the class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The return type matches the data type of the instance variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The name of the method is typically `get` followed by the name of the instance variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `return` keyword exits the method and provides the value to where the method is called\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Then we specify the instance variable we want to return\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***return by value***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why are accessor methods more useful than printing the values in a method in the class?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that accessor methods make it easier to obtain a specific value when they need it. They might also realize that these methods also allow them to use the values to perform calculations in other parts of their program.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b7c20f8-b1d2-4e02-8f80-f87a1a588d7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "badd9ace-b925-4202-8731-972a5b8a707e",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers often have to make decisions about which instance variables should have an accessor method and which should not. In some cases, we might have data in a class that we don't want other classes to have access to or know about.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Putting It All Together",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "badd9ace-b925-4202-8731-972a5b8a707e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ef6780c-eadd-4ed3-a138-b6d98b78efee",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do you think we should decide when to write an access method for an instance variable?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest providing accessor methods when they want other classes to have access to the values stored in an instance variable. Values stored in instance variables that should not be accessible by other classes should not have an accessor method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to write accessor methods in the `Dessert` class. On Level 7, students write accessor methods in the `Dessert` subclass (`Cookie`, `Pie`, `Cupcake`, or `Donut`).",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Accessor Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing and calling accessor methods in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ef6780c-eadd-4ed3-a138-b6d98b78efee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9257831d-810a-428c-89eb-6af1fd37ffff",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9257831d-810a-428c-89eb-6af1fd37ffff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7bbc082a-f6f0-4e0e-9f48-259628fe089e",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7bbc082a-f6f0-4e0e-9f48-259628fe089e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c289a9fe-9f7e-47d8-bb24-dce6bea36cd2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ff9b1e2-732e-46b6-be29-a6b2acc64984",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *A software engineer is designing this class and needs help deciding which instance variables should have accessor methods. Which of these instance variables would you NOT write accessor methods for? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest not writing an accessor method for the `password` instance variable because only the `User` class should have access to this information. Students might also suggest that the `User` class might have a method for comparing what the user entered to the password instance variable instead of using an accessor method that is called in another class to check if the password is correct.",
        "name": "Design Thinking",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider how apps or programs they use function when they forget their password and whether or not they are able to obtain their password if they forget it. Point out that in most cases, they are prompted to change their password if they forget it."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ff9b1e2-732e-46b6-be29-a6b2acc64984",
        "lesson_activity.key": "41a7ecfb-4b1f-468c-997d-7695c8142e22"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5976a507-461c-4f51-ae9d-8950d005f952",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 2 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
