    {
      "key": "6bfbc506-3472-4837-867d-ec65b97d560a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned about the `Scanner` class and how programs obtain input from a user. Let's take a look at some of the methods in the `Scanner` class and how they work.",
        "name": "Scanner Class Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bfbc506-3472-4837-867d-ec65b97d560a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c9287a4b-94a3-407c-8603-561bc4cf6408"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bfd61c9f-866e-4e0d-a7e4-7f2a927ea12d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Scanner Class Methods*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bfd61c9f-866e-4e0d-a7e4-7f2a927ea12d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c9287a4b-94a3-407c-8603-561bc4cf6408"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46f46364-c131-4347-9419-eaf029125897",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What kind of information might you ask the user for in your programs? Which method would you use to get this information?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest getting values for a starting price for a `Dessert` object or asking the user for their name. Students share the methods they would use, such as `nextDouble()` to get the price and `next()` or `nextLine()` to get the user's name.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46f46364-c131-4347-9419-eaf029125897",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c9287a4b-94a3-407c-8603-561bc4cf6408"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d7f718eb-84e5-4225-923a-f2bb3d82de39",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d7f718eb-84e5-4225-923a-f2bb3d82de39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03002ea0-0d28-452a-8209-cf040e6aa8db",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to write accessor methods to get the value stored in an instance variable. But what if we needed to change the value? Today, we're going to learn how we can write methods that allow us to modify the values stored in an instance variable from outside of the class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03002ea0-0d28-452a-8209-cf040e6aa8db",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66e34fb2-6e38-40b7-860c-bbd4b9129ea9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Mutator Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66e34fb2-6e38-40b7-860c-bbd4b9129ea9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28ad64b6-ca2c-4049-b7d1-57a712186a33",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the methods change the values stored in the instance variables. Students may wonder how these methods are able to change the values since instance variables are `private`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28ad64b6-ca2c-4049-b7d1-57a712186a33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90de4384-48da-497d-9335-9e081c199bb0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes we may need to update the value stored in an instance variable, but we still want to protect these instance variables by keeping them `private`. We can write methods in a class that allow us to change the value stored in an instance variable.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Mutator Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90de4384-48da-497d-9335-9e081c199bb0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49c806a0-2a31-4af6-8769-ef24735fc01e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Mutator Methods*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49c806a0-2a31-4af6-8769-ef24735fc01e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "561b017d-9efa-4cce-bfc3-dd86553941f1",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results then practice writing a mutator method in a class.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Mutator Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "561b017d-9efa-4cce-bfc3-dd86553941f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e325f700-201d-47f6-9951-5890bedf8fd1",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Mutator Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e325f700-201d-47f6-9951-5890bedf8fd1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e15b3487-9306-4431-8130-e2a93b7db22f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to share similarities and differences they noticed between accessor methods and mutator methods and between mutator methods and the methods they wrote in their `PainterPlus` class and subclasses."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e15b3487-9306-4431-8130-e2a93b7db22f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ebe893a-708b-4cf7-a471-906d47f9c1f0",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***mutator method***.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax for writing a mutator method:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Method is `public`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Return type is `void`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Name of the method is typically `set` followed by the name of the instance variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Specify a parameter that matches the type of the instance variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Assign the value passed to the parameter to the instance variable\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the syntax for calling a mutator method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Should all instance variables have mutator methods? When would we not want an instance variable to be modified?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of instance variables that might not have mutator methods because those values should not be changed, such as a student ID or social security number.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ebe893a-708b-4cf7-a471-906d47f9c1f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e09afb1d-88e6-4c40-8d7d-cace0ec26bce",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We also saw how we can use methods in the `Scanner` class to obtain values from a user and use these in our programs. However, we have to be careful how we obtain information because of the way some of these methods function in Java.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e09afb1d-88e6-4c40-8d7d-cace0ec26bce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46cbaa72-195b-4a59-8247-02ab2fc3e344",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain common errors using the `nextInt()` method in the `Scanner` class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `nextInt()` method only reads the `int` value and not the new line read from pressing the Enter key\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The following call to the `nextLine()` method captures the new line from pressing the Enter key after providing the `int` value\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> To skip the new line received from pressing Enter after providing the `int` value, we have to add another call to the `nextLine()` method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46cbaa72-195b-4a59-8247-02ab2fc3e344",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2054a788-8eae-40e6-9053-b1e680e6f354",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There are times when we want to make sure that the value is valid before it is assigned to an instance variable. Software engineers have to consider possible values that might be invalid for an instance variable so that these are not accidentally used and cause problems in their programs.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Invalid Values",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2054a788-8eae-40e6-9053-b1e680e6f354",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f78ff33-c0f1-4562-96dd-144f27506156",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Are there values that should be considered invalid for certain instance variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of invalid values, such as a negative x or y location for a `Painter` object or a negative price for a `Dessert` object.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider what they might do if the user provides an invalid value or what happens in apps or programs that they use when an invalid value is provided."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f78ff33-c0f1-4562-96dd-144f27506156",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d2d3ff1-013e-4fa5-ae93-74958284f6ad",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used `if` statements to check if a `Painter` object was facing a specific direction or could move forward. We can also use an `if` statement to check for invalid values. For example, we may want to make sure that a user doesn't enter a negative value for a price or a quantity.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d2d3ff1-013e-4fa5-ae93-74958284f6ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab92ed10-025b-4933-9929-caf49852795c",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Where have you used operators like less than, greater than, or equal?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall using these operators in math class or a previous computer science class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***relational operator*** and introduce the operators.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***Boolean expression*** and demonstrate the examples.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 through 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to write mutator methods in the `Dessert` class. On Level 7, students write mutator methods in the `Dessert` subclass (`Cookie`, `Pie`, `Cupcake`, or `Donut`).",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Mutator Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing and calling mutator methods in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab92ed10-025b-4933-9929-caf49852795c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65d5874f-5bb5-41c0-8f28-d6cb81937bad",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65d5874f-5bb5-41c0-8f28-d6cb81937bad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3192c1f-d281-4f25-8174-29d989d1150a",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3192c1f-d281-4f25-8174-29d989d1150a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ea827b18-d279-4957-ab78-eba36aad43a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ca91ad0-8612-4003-b89e-35ac9d43e284",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about the components of a class and making design decisions about how we access and work with its instance variables. These are decisions software engineers have to make every day as they design and write programs!",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ca91ad0-8612-4003-b89e-35ac9d43e284",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c15ca18c-ccc3-414b-b801-9363c3f7b2f9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "757b634c-d84f-4ef6-905f-1dd00e643c67",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share aspects of their program they enjoyed or how they solved the problem and identify areas of improvement to strengthen their programming skills. Students also share any questions or misconceptions they may have.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "757b634c-d84f-4ef6-905f-1dd00e643c67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c15ca18c-ccc3-414b-b801-9363c3f7b2f9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90a5d96a-3ba8-4a61-a72e-39f9b2c67f46",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 2 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90a5d96a-3ba8-4a61-a72e-39f9b2c67f46",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c15ca18c-ccc3-414b-b801-9363c3f7b2f9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2852d49d-8130-4c5c-9f99-4d0c22de26d3",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
