    {
      "key": "6e1b5b68-9cfc-4860-a2b6-8139a271ec32",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e1b5b68-9cfc-4860-a2b6-8139a271ec32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56058967-2c1a-44ff-a2b6-980758055f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a7613a5e-a3c9-4f82-a6be-b103fea5930f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous unit, we worked with data as 1D arrays to answer questions and find information.",
        "name": "Telling a Story",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a7613a5e-a3c9-4f82-a6be-b103fea5930f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc124ce2-254a-4441-8242-69685d6180db"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59bc2e8f-a14a-4846-9ded-69dfdba6d730",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might you tell the story behind the data you worked with in the previous unit as a visualization?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas about how they might visualize the data they worked with in the previous unit, such as displaying shapes in different sizes to correlate with the number of values that meet specific criteria or convey the largest and smallest values in a dataset.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students consider how they would create these visualizations in The Theater. Ask students if they would create a static image or an animation and how these approaches would impact the effectiveness of the message."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59bc2e8f-a14a-4846-9ded-69dfdba6d730",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc124ce2-254a-4441-8242-69685d6180db"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb420fc3-940a-4305-ae98-8a643c17f12b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb420fc3-940a-4305-ae98-8a643c17f12b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2d8e7dd-fcc0-4a70-a7b7-94078d089283",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "So far, the instance variables and methods we have written in our classes can only be accessed by an instance of the class. However, there are special types of variables and methods that can be used without an object. Today, we'll learn about the `static` keyword and how we can use it with variables and methods in a class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2d8e7dd-fcc0-4a70-a7b7-94078d089283",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "589c9bc6-e639-4791-bfe6-f0da1d38b306",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Static Variables and Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "589c9bc6-e639-4791-bfe6-f0da1d38b306",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f87135a-bdf1-49af-8b8d-8179ff568014",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the class contains a static variable that is increased by one in the constructor. They also notice that the value is updated each time an object is created, and that the `static` keyword is also used in the method signature. Students may wonder what the `static` keyword means and when they might use static variables and methods instead of instance variables and methods they call on an object."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f87135a-bdf1-49af-8b8d-8179ff568014",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3681bb0e-36c7-4a08-9554-97851f6bf498",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall that each object gets its own copy of the instance variables that are declared in a class.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Static Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3681bb0e-36c7-4a08-9554-97851f6bf498",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0320fead-4dee-48e3-bd5f-e0429e9bb938",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes we need to represent information that is shared by all instances of a class. Rather than declaring instance variables for these values, we can use static variables.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0320fead-4dee-48e3-bd5f-e0429e9bb938",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f862d16-bae7-494a-8b23-8496843bba84",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The static Keyword"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f862d16-bae7-494a-8b23-8496843bba84",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "335192ed-e827-4a90-ba88-9d54048a76cf",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `static` keyword and define ***static variable***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Static Variables*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "335192ed-e827-4a90-ba88-9d54048a76cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3a2b775c-9f81-4928-ae23-0cc51017a510",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Static variables allow us to represent values that are shared by all instances of a class. The syntax for declaring and accessing a static variable is similar to other types of variables, but there are some differences as well.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3a2b775c-9f81-4928-ae23-0cc51017a510",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0699f66-46a2-4b4c-80d6-d755d78efbb3",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that static variables belong to the class and introduce the syntax for accessing a static variable.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students consider what they think it means in the `main` method. Guide students to realizing that since the `main` method is where the program starts running, Java does not need an object of the class to be created to access it. You can ask questions like:\n* *What is the purpose of the `main` method?*\n* *Where do we typically write the `main` method?*\n* *Would it make sense to need to create an object before Java can execute the `main` method?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0699f66-46a2-4b4c-80d6-d755d78efbb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6f679c5-435a-4e96-8458-f37f2ff0dc57",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `static` keyword can also be used with methods. Like static variables, these can be called on the class instead of an object.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Static Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6f679c5-435a-4e96-8458-f37f2ff0dc57",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76d2205a-4945-45b7-ab51-f99c6ecc0254",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Static Methods*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***instance method*** and ***static method***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the rules and syntax for a static method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate calling a static method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 through 8. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to create and use a static variable. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to create and use a static method. On Level 8, students complete a choice level to create and use both static variables and methods.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Static Variables and Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of static methods.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of creating and using static variables and methods."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76d2205a-4945-45b7-ab51-f99c6ecc0254",
        "lesson_activity.key": "21c6cef1-a732-4dba-9651-a44ca1b36599"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ff01a3f-01d1-4fb5-adf6-304ff055d1a8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We've now seen how static variables and methods work and some ways that they are used in different programs. Depending on the needs of our programs, there are several reasons why we might use a static variable instead of an instance variable or a static method instead of an instance method.",
        "name": "Using Static Variables and Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ff01a3f-01d1-4fb5-adf6-304ff055d1a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56cf91bb-fd7e-4fd4-9002-b58bdb8120e4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4239727-0b57-49db-b6ef-a8e070245567",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When do you think static variables and methods would be useful?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest scenarios for using static variables, such as to keep track of the number of `Student` objects in a program for a school or to represent a discount on an item. Students also suggest scenarios for using static methods, such as to perform calculations in a `Calculator` class or to represent a behavior that does not use any instance variables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce example uses for static variables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce example uses for static methods.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to share additional ideas for scenarios where static variables and methods would be useful."
          }
        ]
      },
